        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>As the observed FWHM of the spectrum wing is 450km/s (Figure 3),  our choice of the line width is appropriate. As the width of the excess blue side is as wide as ~150km/s (Figure 3), the spectral resolution 2.58km/s is sufficient to resolve the velocity gradient in the source. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>With a resolution 0.14 arcsec, which is equal to the diameter of a circle inscribed in the caustic of the best-fitted model, one can successfully reconstruct the source profile from lensed quadruple images. The largest angular scale 2.0 arcsec is given by the observed IRAM images in Figure 1. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The weakest component is redshifted image A for a velocity range from 25km/s to 225km/s whose flux density is 10.8 mJy (Table 1). We expect a mean change in the flux by 7 percent due to the line-of-sight structures. As the standard deviation of the flux change is almost equal to the mean value (Takahashi and Inoue 2014 reference [8]), we require a detection of flux change by 7/2=3.5 percent of image A. Thus, for 5 sigma detection, we need a sensitivity of 10.8*0.035/5=0.076 mJy.  With such a sensitivity, we can detect an image distortion in one component of the quadrupolar pattern at the 0.35 mJy/0.076 mJy =4.7 sigma level if a perturber resides at a point between image A and C. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
